Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: 2024 VCE Texts and Traditions external assessment report

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The overall standard of student responses in the 2024 examination was very high. It is clear that students are preparing across the whole study design: the set text, relevant themes, and in particular the passages for special study. Most students can, at the least, provide relevant responses to questions.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Higher-scoring responses answered in line with the VCAA published command terms, which in the 2024 examination were almost identical to previous years. The command terms are typical of scriptural scholarship, and are therefore typical of most VCE Texts and Traditions exams. The command terms were:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The short-answer questions in Part 1 and most of the essay questions have multiple parts; this provides a guide for students to structure their responses.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: It is safe to assume that questions will be different from previous years, especially the parts of compulsory Question 4, so it is advised that students read all parts of the chosen question. High-scoring responses answered the actual question that was asked.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Most students paid attention to the multiple parts of the questions, and used these parts to help structure their responses.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Students are reminded to write their answers in English. There are no extra marks for words or phrases written in Hebrew, Greek or Arabic.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Higher-scoring responses incorporated quotations. However, if students are unsure whether the quotation is accurate, it is preferable to paraphrase a scholar - that is, not to use quotation marks but rather to write, for example, 'Scholar A says that ...'

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Students are to be commended on following instructions in the Answer Book. This enabled students to answer questions more fully, especially Question 4.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: It is important for students to indicate the correct answer at the top of the appropriate page in the Answer Book, and to ensure that only one question is answered per page. It is not necessary to write out the question. Responses that are continued in the extra space provided must be labelled to indicate they are 'continued', so that the examiner knows to continue reading and awarding marks.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Note: Student responses reproduced in this report have not been corrected for grammar, spelling or factual information.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: This report provides sample answers or an indication of what answers may have included. Unless otherwise stated, these are not intended to be exemplary or complete responses.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The statistics in this report may be subject to rounding resulting in a total more or less than 100 per cent.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: This part of the examination is almost always from Unit 3 Outcomes 1 and 2. Questions 1-3 are worth 10 marks each. Each question has two to three parts, and each part has marks awarded to it.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: High-scoring responses answered each part of the chosen questions, and demonstrated familiarity with the command terms in addressing the questions.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Lower-scoring responses tended to not answer all parts of the question, not follow the command terms, include material that was not directly relevant to the question, or were too brief to fully answer the question.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Some students wrote very long responses, almost to the length of an essay, going into more detail than was required to answer the question.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Statistics for this examination cover all four tradition strand questions; it is not possible to provide statistics on individual questions. The average mark for Questions 1-3 across the four tradition strands ranged between 5.6 and 6.1. Five to 10 per cent of attempted responses did not address the question.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: It is important that students show an understanding of specialist terms by providing a clear definition or by demonstrating understanding through their discussion. Responses can then be marked within that understanding of the term.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Part 1 - Extended responses

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The extended responses are directly related to the passages, themes and ideas from the 2025 passages for special study. This part of the examination is almost always from Unit 3 outcomes 1 and 2. Questions 1-3 were worth 10 marks each. All the questions consisted of two or three parts, and each part had marks awarded to it. High-scoring answers addressed each part of the question, clearly signposting the individual parts of the question, and often in separate paragraphs.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Low-scoring responses did not answer all parts of the question or included non-relevant information or discussion. Setting a time allocation may assist.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Students must show care to respond to the set text they have studied.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Qur'an

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: In Question 1 from the Qur'an section, students were required to use two examples from Surah 19 to outline the concern of Maryam, explain Maryam's predicament and discuss how her people reacted to her miraculous conception.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The following is from a high-scoring response:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: After angel Jibraeel descended by the command of Allah and announced that Maryam would give birth to a child she was concerned of how she could possibly give birth when... After she had given birth her concern changed into how she would return to her village ...  Just as Maryam worried, the people of her village upon seeing a baby ... began to question how she could possibly have given birth when... However, after Isa spoke on behalf of his mother the people ceased their queries understanding that her son was ...

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: John

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Students were required to explain why examples of fulfilment of messianic prophecy included in the Passion narrative are used for John's audience, using two examples and explaining the significance of each example.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The following is an example from a high-scoring response:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: There are numerous examples of fulfillment of messianic prophecies in the Passion narrative. Such fulfillments of prophecy were of profound significance ... as it communicated to them that their faith ... One such prophecy that is fulfilled ... is that of the suffering servant (Isaiah 52 and 53) [which] speaks of ... Another messianic prophecy that is fulfilled in the passion narrative is that of Zechariah ...

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Luke

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Students were required to explain the significance of Chapter 2 and discuss what the chapter tells us about the Kingdom of God, using two examples to support their response.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The following is an example from a high-scoring response:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Chapter 2, which outlines the birth and childhood of Jesus, significantly underscores the beginning of Jesus' life, death and resurrection, and frames the understanding of his identity ... The chapter further emphasises the proclamation of the kingdom of God ... The boy Jesus in the temple indicates this understanding ... in the role that Jesus plays in promoting the kingdom. The chapter confirms their place within the kingdom ...

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: High-scoring responses addressed all three parts of the question.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Many lower-scoring responses provided content and discussion more appropriate to past examination questions.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Some low-scoring responses did not name a theme from the set text, did not name a particular period of history later than the formation of the set text or did not discuss how the later interpretations affected the religious tradition. Some lower-scoring responses provided historical summaries but did not link them to the questions.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Part 2 - Exegetical response

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Questions 5-7

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The mean mark for the exegetical response was 18 out of a possible 30 marks. Approximately 45 per cent achieved 20 or more marks, and 46 per cent achieved 10 to 19 marks.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: High-scoring responses demonstrated:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: a confident grasp of the required exegetical elements - context, literary analysis, themes, significance for original receivers or audience of the selected excerpts

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: solid knowledge of a range of scholars, and an ability to integrate commentary meaningfully, rather than simply quoting or listing

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: an exploration of textual layers with nuance, demonstrating understanding not only of the surface meaning but also of broader thematic, structural and theological implications.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Lower-scoring responses included:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: sections of the exegetical exercise that were not completed

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: references or comparisons to other writings or scholarly opinion not relevant to the passage being analysed

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: references to other passages from the set text, which did not add to understanding of the context nor the analysis of the passage

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: sections from the passage that were misquoted, or analysis of ideas not found in the passage.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Part 3 - Essay

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: The marks allocated for the essay component of the examination remains stable from year to year, with the average mark for the essay questions this year 16 out of a possible 30 marks. Approximately 37 per cent achieved 20 marks or more; 44 per cent achieved between 10 and 19 marks.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: High-scoring responses usually included:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: discussion directly relevant to the question, including addressing key terms and theological concepts in the question

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: discussion of all parts of the question, including whether the examples or evidence were from the set text or excerpts, and the correct number of examples as nominated by the question

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: skilful scholarly opinion, including direct quotes from scholars

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: clear signposting or 'topic sentences' in the style used in English essays, used to structure the discussion of the question.

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: Lower-scoring responses included:

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: discussion that did not answer all sections of the question

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: apparent misinterpretation of key terms, which led to inaccurate responses

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: references to other writings and scholars that were not directly relevant to the question

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: apparent use of prepared answers, without reference to the actual question

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: brief, or repetitive and sometimes lengthy, responses without addressing the question

Subject: Texts and Traditions
SectionHeaderContent: responses answering sections of the examination paper that did not apply to the relevant tradition.
